{# Gemma 3 native user prompt for paragraph summarization.
   Wrapped automatically by Ollama into <start_of_turn>user ... <end_of_turn>
   <start_of_turn>model. Per Gemma 3's chat template (see
   `ollama show gemma3:27b --modelfile`) the model has no distinct system
   role — Google's convention is to put all substantive instructions in the
   user turn. We therefore put the full set of rules here, ahead of the
   transcript payload, then restate the binding constraints once more at the
   end so they sit nearest the assistant turn (recency-window pattern).

   Style follows the Gemma 3 IT post-training convention from the model card
   ( https://huggingface.co/google/gemma-3-27b-it ): plain instructions,
   declarative tone, no role-play preamble. #}
Task: write an abstractive summary of the following podcast episode transcript.

Summary requirements:
- Synthesize the substantive ideas in your own words. Do not copy sentences verbatim from the transcript.
- Focus on the episode's key decisions, arguments, lessons learned, and substantive insights.
- Exclude advertisements, sponsorship reads, listener-mail housekeeping, and meta show-talk.
- Do not include speaker names. Do not include direct quotations.
- Stay strictly grounded in the transcript. Do not add facts the transcript does not support.

Output format:
- Return plain text only — no markdown, no headings, no bullet lists, no code blocks, no JSON.
- Begin the response with the first sentence of the summary. Do not include a preamble such as "Here is the summary" or "Summary:".
- Separate paragraphs with a single blank line.
- Write in clear, declarative third-person prose.

{% if title -%}
Episode title: {{ title }}

{% endif -%}
Transcript:
{{ transcript }}

Now write the summary. Target length: {{ paragraphs_min }}–{{ paragraphs_max }} paragraphs.

Reminder of the binding constraints:
- Abstractive, synthesized prose; no verbatim sentence copying.
- No speaker names, no direct quotations.
- Plain text only; no markdown, no headings, no bullet lists, no preamble.
- Begin immediately with the first sentence of the summary.
